'''Okada Kamo Shrine''' (おかだかもじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|WD=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} located in Kamo-chō Kita, {{ill|lt=Kizugawa City|Q990352|WD=Q990352|1=Kizugawa, Kyoto}}, {{ill|lt=Kyoto Prefecture|Q120730|WD=Q120730|1=Kyoto Prefecture}}. It is a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|WD=Q134917286}} ({{ill|lt=Shikidai Taisha|Q134917288|WD=Q134917288|1=Shikinai Taisha}}), and under the {{ill|lt=modern shrine ranking system|Q712534|WD=Q712534|lt=former shrine rank|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}} it was classified as a {{ill|lt=Gōsha|Q134917316|WD=Q134917316|1=Gō-sha}}. It enshrines {{ill|lt=Kamo Taketsunumi no Mikoto|Q11634939|WD=Q11634939|lt=Taketsunumi no Mikoto|1=Kamotaketsunumi no Mikoto}}, the ancestral deity of the {{ill|lt=Kamo Agatanushi clan|Q2975287|WD=Q2975287|1=Kamo clan}}.

=== History ===
[[File:Okada-Kamo-jinja, torii.jpg|thumb|220px|right|{{center|Torii}}]]
According to a fragment of the *Yamashiro no Kuni Fudoki*, Taketsunumi no Mikoto traveled from Katsuragi in {{ill|lt=Yamato Province|Q907495|WD=Q907495|1=Yamato Province}}, passed through Okada Kamo in Yamashiro Province, and came to rest at {{ill|lt=Kamo Mioya Shrine|Q701620|WD=Q701620|1=Shimogamo Shrine}} (Shimogamo Shrine) in northern Kyoto. It is said that during the reign of {{ill|lt=Emperor Sujin|Q333530|WD=Q333530|1=Emperor Sujin}}, the Kamo clan received a divided spirit from Shimogamo Shrine and founded this shrine at Okada Kamo, a place associated with Taketsunumi no Mikoto.

The earliest documentary reference appears in the *{{ill|lt=Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku|Q1052981|WD=Q1052981|1=Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku}}*, in an entry dated the 27th day of the first month of {{ill|lt=Jōgan (Japan)|Q1075635|WD=Q1075635|lt=Jōgan|1=Jōgan}} 1 ({{ill|lt=859|Q23897|WD=Q23897|1=859}}), which records that the shrine was granted the divine rank of Junior Fifth Rank, Upper Grade ({{ill|lt=shinkai|Q11591025|WD=Q11591025|1=Shinkai (divine rank)}}).

In the *{{ill|lt=Engishiki|Q1342448|WD=Q1342448|1=Engishiki}}* {{ill|lt=Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|WD=Q11064932|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}} compiled in {{ill|lt=Enchō (era)|Q1327274|WD=Q1327274|lt=Enchō|1=Enchō}} 5 ({{ill|lt=927|Q30470|WD=Q30470|1=927}}), the shrine is listed under {{ill|lt=Yamashiro Province|Q749276|WD=Q749276|1=Yamashiro Province}}, {{ill|lt=Sōraku District|Q1154661|WD=Q1154661|1=Sōraku District, Kyoto}} as “Okada Kamo Shrine, Major, Tsukinami and Niiname,” placing it among the Shikidai Taisha and noting that it received offerings at the court’s {{ill|lt=Tsukinami Festival|Q11516161|WD=Q11516161|1=Tsukinami-no-Matsuri}} and {{ill|lt=Niiname Festival|Q11501518|WD=Q11501518|1=Niiname-no-Matsuri}}.

The shrine was originally located north of its present site (on the bank of the {{ill|lt=Kizugawa River (Kyoto)|Q3746236|WD=Q3746236|lt=Kizugawa River|1=Kizu River}}, where the site known as “Kamo Daimyōjin Ruins” remains). However, repeated flooding caused by changes in the river’s course led to its relocation to the current location. The present site is said to be the former location of the Okada Detached Palace of {{ill|lt=Empress Genmei|Q233224|WD=Q233224|1=Empress Genmei}}. After the palace fell into disuse, villagers established a shrine to preserve the former palace grounds, calling it “Tenjin Shrine.” Okada Kamo Shrine was later relocated into that precinct. Today, the Tenmangū stands as a subsidiary shrine within the grounds.

